In [5]:
# Ensure we use the correct airport identifier
for _, row in airports.iterrows():
    airport_code = row['iata_code']  # Use IATA code (e.g., JFK, LAX)
    if pd.notna(airport_code):  # Ignore rows without valid IATA codes
        G.add_node(airport_code, pos=(row['latitude_deg'], row['longitude_deg']))
In [6]:
# Use KDTree for fast nearest-neighbor search
coords = list(zip(airports["latitude_deg"], airports["longitude_deg"]))
identifiers = list(airports["iata_code"])
valid_data = [(id, coord) for id, coord in zip(identifiers, coords) if pd.notna(id)]
identifiers, coords = zip(*valid_data)  # Remove None values

tree = KDTree(coords)
for i, coord in enumerate(coords):
    distances, indices = tree.query(coord, k=6)  # Connect to 5 nearest airports
    for dist, idx in zip(distances[1:], indices[1:]):  # Skip itself
        neighbor_id = identifiers[idx]
        neighbor_coord = coords[idx]
        real_distance = haversine(coord, neighbor_coord)
        G.add_edge(identifiers[i], neighbor_id, weight=real_distance)
In [7]:
# Function to find shortest path
def find_shortest_path(graph, source, target):
    return nx.shortest_path(graph, source=source, target=target, weight='weight'), nx.shortest_path_length(graph, source=source, target=target, weight='weight')

else:

In [18]:
# Function to find alternative airports
def find_alternate_airports(source, min_runway_length=2500):
    if source not in G or source not in pos:
        return []

    valid_runway_airports = set(runways[runways['length_ft'] >= min_runway_length]['iata_code'].dropna().unique())
    if source in pos:
        distances, indices = tree.query(pos[source], k=10)
        nearest_airports = [identifiers[idx] for idx in indices]
        alternate_airports = [ap for ap in nearest_airports if ap in valid_runway_airports and ap in pos]
        return alternate_airports[:5]
    return []
